document.originaltext: Now the rite of the first shaving of the head and piercing of the ears. Prepare the sacred vases according to the rules. The Brahmin should worship the sacred vases according to the rules. Give argha to the sun. vākya: "I wish to make the worship of the sacred vase for the rite of the shaving of the head and piercing of the ears for a boy from such and such gotra having such and such name." Salutation with argha to Śrī Sūrya. Salutation with flowers. The worship of the sacred vase should be finished according to the sāit. The thakāli should bring the boy holding his hand and make him sit on a svastika. Purifying of the involved persons etc. reciting the rakṣohaṇaṃ, the adhya no, the tejo 'si. Sprinkle water from the arghyapātra reciting the devasya tvā. The boy should worship the kalaśa by throwing rice. After reciting the śāntipuṣṭika, give the dvāphvaḥ svã. Worship the lamp, the wooden measuring vessel and the keys reciting the agnir mūrdhā divaḥ and the trātāram indram. He should wave with a plate of svagã, with lamp, wooden measuring vessel and keys reciting the ausraghnam. Offering of oil reciting the kāṇḍātkāṇḍāt or the dīrghāyutvāya.... Do the same below i.e. on the feet. Put grains of unhusked rice on the head of the boy reciting the dīrghāyutvāya. Incense etc., svagã, blessing. Perform ārati with waving a lamp on the siphã. Scatter the material from the siphã on the head of the boy reciting the yāḥ phalinīr. Again ārati reciting the tejo 'si. pratiṣṭhā reciting the mano jūtir. Wave the thāybhū on which a candramaṇḍala is drawn reciting the vayaṃ. Worship the hands of the maternal uncle, sister of the father and barber. The razor should be handed over to the maternal uncle. Hand over the plate with the candramaṇḍala together with a small bamboo plate to the nini. Put the copper pot together with curd and grinded grey sesame paste on the fire. The dīrghāyutvāya and the savitrā prasūta daivyā.... The preceeding mantra is for pouring warm water by the father on the head of the boy before shaving the hair. The thakāli should pour cold water reciting the svasti na indro. Divide the hair with a porcupine tail reciting again the dīrghāyutvāya. Tie the hair. Evidence: "In the east above the forehead, a piece of the Banyan tree, and in the south above the right ear, a piece of the country udumbara, in the south above the right ear, a piece of the aśvattha, and in the west also a piece of the fig tree. In the middle a golden coin together with darbha grass at the back; in the middle, on the place of the pañcaśikhā the rule for the cūḍākarṇa is remembered." Start from the east reciting the oṣadhe trāyasva.... In the same manner in the south, north and west. Immediately after tying the pieces of wood and the top knot the shaving of the hair should be started. The mantra while taking the razor by the maternal uncle is the following: śivo nāmāsi. He should recite it half. The mantra while touching the hair with the razor is the following: ni vartayāmy uṣe. The mantra while shaving is the following: yenāvapatsavitā kṣureṇa. The hair should be collected by the sister of the father. The father should pour warm water on the head of the boy reciting the savitrā prasūta daivyā. The mantra for shaving is tryāyuṣaṃ yamadagneḥ and ya bhūriścarā divaṃ. Recite the śloka loudly. Make an imagination of all the hair being shaved. Afterwards he should hand over the razor to the barber. Pierce the right ear with a golden needle reciting the bhadraṃ karṇebhiḥ.... Pierce on the right side i.e. the right ear with a silver spike reciting a whole oṃ tīvrān.... Afterwards the nāyaḥ should welcome the boy carried by the mother and make him sit on a place prepared by a svastika. The barber should shave the head except for the tuft. Give the barber a piece of sweet meat. Send the hair into the river adding the mixture of curd and beaten rice. The boy should take a ritual bath with khau and a sarvoṣadhi. The nāyaḥ should welcome the boy and make him sit on a place prepared by a svastika. Purifying by sprinkling water from the arghyapātra reciting the oṃ devasya tvā. Throw pieces of fruits over the participants. Hang the ākāśamālā on reciting the oṃ tava vāyu.... The boy should throw rice on the sacred vases reciting the śuddhaśāntaṃ. He should wave with a plate of svagã, with a lamp, the wooden measuring vessel and iron keys reciting the asuraghnam. Rub sandalwood paste on the head. Draw a svastika on the head. The Jośī should throw brown sesame seeds on the head. Bind the Kumaḥkaḥ thread around on the head reciting the rakṣohaṇaṃ. Bind a silk thread around the head reciting the pavitre 'stho. Stick a porcupine bristle, a traditional comb, a piece of Udumbara wood, a bit of black soot, Kuśa grass and a peacock feather into the hair reciting the namaḥ sambhavāya ca. Hand over sandalwood paste, svagã and the dress to the boy. The mantra for sandalwood paste is the yad adya kac. For the vermilion the tvaṃ yaviṣṭha dāśuṣo. For svagã: the dadhi krāvṇo. For the dress: the vasoḥ pavitram asi. Place cakraphaṇi on the head reciting the trātāram indram. Perform ārati with waving a lamp on the siphã reciting the yāḥ phalinīr. Repeat it three times reciting the tejo 'si. Throw popped rice on the boy reciting the mano jūtir. The Brāhmaṇa etc. should be given food with a ritual decision and dakṣiṇā and reciting the mantra . Keep snacks on the sacred vase reciting the svasti bhavanto me brūtāṃ svasti. Offering of snacks to the sacred vase. Worship of the Veda reciting the ājighrakalaśaṃ mahyā tveti, the ghṛtaṃ ghṛtapāvānaḥ. Dissolve the nyāsa. Release the sacred vases i.e. the deities in the sacred vases reciting the ud vayaṃ tamasas. Sent bali offerings to different places. Give abhiṣeka together with a ritual mirror. Give a tikā of sandalwood paste etc., svagã and blessings to the boy reciting the devasya tvā, the yad adya kac, the tvaṃ yaviṣṭha dāśuṣo and the dadhi krāvṇo. Blessings reciting the mūrdhānaṃ divo, the bhadraṃ karṇebhiḥ, "Hail to all". Clean the mirror reciting the pūrṇacandrasūkta. Release the witnesses such as Sūrya, Navagraha etc.. Release Kaumāri. Here ends the chapter on the shaving of the head and piercing of the ears.
